Wu Wei    Is actionless action or spontanenity...  comes from within
from the center  as many Taoists believe is the way of Tao.

Wu Shih is to do without having to struggle, force, meddle,
interfer...leaving others to find their own way; in other words, people
will be content without others manipulating or interferring with their
way of life.   It is the way of the ancients to which Lao Tzu and
Chuang Tzu pointed.

63 is again referring to the ancients; the next sentence refers to a
balance or a pivot;  it is said in CT, in ancient places,  cultivation
was not needed, as when the people were as the ancients living in small
isolated villages, however both Lao Tzu and Chunag Tzu (who appreciated
the ways of Lao Tzu ) believed that the interference of rulers, sages,
emperors and other leaders destroyed the balance of people's lives and
felt that the old ways of non-action or action less action and not
interference would help and cultivation became a topic and a practice
for some Taoists sages and adepts.   Today, there are those who do not
practice any type of cultivation of wu wei or wu shih and there are
those who do have a practice of cultivation.  I find it all... a way of
sorts... of this and that... under the large umbrella of what we call
the Taoist way.

