Shi means event, affair, and has overtones of trouble.
Sheng shi shi sheng is a symmetrical sentence where
sheng means birth, to be born, to give birth to, to arise,
to give rise to, and here it means: to create trouble
begets trouble. Another relevant expression is ping-an
wu-shi, which means that everything goes well. So
meddling is a correct translation for shi. Wu-wei and
wu-shi to me both mean to efface oneself in favour of
what happens, without meddling in it or interfering
with it. To me non-interference, non-obstruction,
non-resistance, making space for what happens by
emptying oneself out and letting the situation act one,
etc. are implications of wu-wei and wu-shi.

Tang Huyen
